{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596321"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:11:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:11:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15402"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15402"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.04,0.38,0.04,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63576"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8093"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49030"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20853"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63576"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHaemorrhoids are a common anorectal condition and may occur in about 50% of adults over age 50.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"With regards to haemorrhoids, which one of the following is most correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["They only occur above the dentate line","Pregnancy reduces the risk of developing haemorrhoids","Prolonged sitting is a key aetiological factor","They usually result from primary bacterial infection","They arise from submucosal arteriovenous cushions that become enlarged or prolapsed"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhoids\u003C/strong\u003E are normal vascular cushions in the anal canal that become pathological when enlarged or prolapsed. They contain arteriovenous channels, smooth muscle, and connective tissue that aid in maintaining anal continence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E actually increases rather than reduces the risk of haemorrhoid development due to increased intra-abdominal pressure and progesterone-mediated tissue relaxation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemorrhoids are found on both sides of the\u003Cstrong\u003E dentate line\u003C/strong\u003E. They can be either internal (above) or external (below). \u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial infection\u003C/strong\u003E is not a primary cause, though secondary infection can occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged sitting\u003C/strong\u003E as a cause is a popular misconception, with no good evidence to support this idea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors include chronic constipation, prolonged straining, pregnancy, and increased intra-abdominal pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemorrhoids are cushions of submucosal arteriovenous tissue that become pathological when enlarged or prolapsed","Pregnancy increases risk of haemorrhoids due to increased pelvic pressure and hormonal changes","Haemorrhoids are classified as internal (above dentate line) or external (below dentate line)"],"references":["Mott T, Latimer K, Edwards C. Hemorrhoids: Diagnosis and Treatment Options. Am Fam Physician. 2018 Feb 1;97(3):172-179. PMID: 29431977.","Sun Z, Migaly J. Review of Hemorrhoid Disease: Presentation and Management. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2016 Mar;29(1):22-9. doi: 10.1055/s-0035-1568144. PMID: 26929748; PMCID: PMC4755769.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49030"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15402"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49030"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T16:47:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T16:48:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8093"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63576"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/266"},"a